### Question B — 14 Marks **[KTU University Exam — Dec 2023 Model — Alternative]**

**(a) [7 marks]** Compute the modular inverse of the key matrix $\mathbf{K} = \begin{bmatrix} 3 & 2 \\ 5 & 7 \end{bmatrix}$ modulo 26. Show every step of the Extended Euclidean Algorithm and the adjugate computation.

**(b) [7 marks]** Using the inverse obtained in part (a), decrypt the ciphertext `"DLLE"` step by step. Then describe **two improvements** that can be made to the basic Hill Cipher to strengthen it.

#### Model Solution

**Part (a) — Modular Inverse of K (7 marks):**

**Step 1 — Compute the determinant:** (1 mark)
$$\det(\mathbf{K}) = (3)(7) - (2)(5) = 21 - 10 = 11$$

**Step 2 — Find $11^{-1} \bmod 26$ using Extended Euclidean Algorithm:** (3 marks)

$$
\begin{aligned}
26 &= 2 \cdot 11 + 4 \\
11 &= 2 \cdot 4 + 3 \\
4 &= 1 \cdot 3 + 1 \\
3 &= 3 \cdot 1 + 0
\end{aligned}
$$

Back-substitution:
$$1 = 4 - 1 \cdot 3 = 4 - (11 - 2 \cdot 4) = 3 \cdot 4 - 1 \cdot 11 = 3(26 - 2 \cdot 11) - 1 \cdot 11 = 3 \cdot 26 - 7 \cdot 11$$

Therefore $11 \cdot (-7) \equiv 1 \pmod{26}$, giving $11^{-1} \equiv -7 \equiv 19 \pmod{26}$.

**Verification:** $11 \times 19 = 209 = 8 \times 26 + 1$ ✓ (0.5 mark)

**Step 3 — Build the adjugate:** (1 mark)
$$\text{adj}(\mathbf{K}) = \begin{bmatrix} 7 & -2 \\ -5 & 3 \end{bmatrix}$$

**Step 4 — Multiply by $\det^{-1} = 19$ and reduce mod 26:** (1.5 marks)

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathbf{K}^{-1} &= 19 \cdot \begin{bmatrix} 7 & -2 \\ -5 & 3 \end{bmatrix} \bmod 26 \\
&= \begin{bmatrix} 133 & -38 \\ -95 & 57 \end{bmatrix} \bmod 26 \\
&= \begin{bmatrix} 3 & 14 \\ 9 & 5 \end{bmatrix}
\end{aligned}
$$

---

**Part (b) — Decryption + Improvements (7 marks):**

**Decryption steps:** (4 marks)

Convert `"DLLE"` → $[3, 11, 11, 4]$ → blocks $\mathbf{C}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 11 \end{bmatrix}$, $\mathbf{C}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 11 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix}$.

For block 1:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathbf{P}_1 &= \begin{bmatrix} 3 & 14 \\ 9 & 5 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 11 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 163 \\ 82 \end{bmatrix} \equiv \begin{bmatrix} 7 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix} \pmod{26} \Rightarrow \text{"HE"}
\end{aligned}
$$

For block 2:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathbf{P}_2 &= \begin{bmatrix} 3 & 14 \\ 9 & 5 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 11 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 89 \\ 119 \end{bmatrix} \equiv \begin{bmatrix} 11 \\ 15 \end{bmatrix} \pmod{26} \Rightarrow \text{"LP"}
\end{aligned}
$$

**Recovered plaintext: "HELP"** ✓ (1 mark)

**Two Improvements** (3 marks — 1.5 each):

1. **Increase the block size $n$:** A 3×3 or larger key makes the cipher resistant to brute-force key search (number of valid keys grows roughly as $26^{n^2}$). It also obscures single-letter and digram frequency statistics because each ciphertext letter depends on *n* plaintext letters.

2. **Combine with a non-linear step (S-box):** Plain Hill Cipher is **completely linear** and hence vulnerable to a known-plaintext attack that recovers $\mathbf{K}$ by solving a linear system. Inserting a non-linear substitution layer (analogous to AES's SubBytes) breaks this linearity and resists known-plaintext attacks.

3. *(Alternative third improvement — bonus credit)* **Use a non-standard alphabet of size $m$ where $\gcd(m, \det(\mathbf{K})) = 1$ is more easily satisfied**, or include case preservation, digits, and punctuation as a richer symbol set.

---

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Pitfall Callout — Where Students Commonly Lose Marks**
> 1. **Forgetting the `mod 26` after each row computation in matrix multiplication** — every intermediate sum must be reduced mod 26, not just the final answer. (-1 to -2 marks)
> 2. **Using a key matrix with $\gcd(\det, 26) \neq 1$** — the program will crash at runtime or produce garbled output. Always validate the key first. (-1 mark)
> 3. **Incorrect sign handling in the 2×2 inverse** — students often forget to negate $b$ and $c$ in the adjugate. A foolproof trick: swap diagonal entries, negate off-diagonals. (-1 mark)
> 4. **Confusing the modular inverse with the regular integer inverse** — for example, $11^{-1} \bmod 26$ is **19**, not $1/11$. Use Extended Euclidean, not division. (-2 marks)
> 5. **Ignoring padding for odd-length plaintexts** — `if (length % 2 != 0) pad with 'X';` is mandatory. The examiner will test with an odd-length input. (-1 mark)
> 6. **In Java specifically: forgetting to make `mod26` return a positive result for negative arguments** — Java's `%` operator can return negative values; always add 26 when `x < 0`. (-1 mark)

