# 📘 SECTION 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

> [!NOTE]
> **DES (Data Encryption Standard)** is a symmetric-key block cipher standardized by the U.S. National Bureau of Standards (now NIST) in **1977** as **FIPS PUB 46**. It encrypts **64-bit** plaintext blocks using a **64-bit key** (of which only **56 bits** are effective, the remaining 8 bits are parity bits), through **16 rounds** of a **Feistel network** structure, producing a 64-bit ciphertext block.

The DES algorithm is governed by the following hard parameters:

| Parameter | Value |
| :--- | :--- |
| **Block Size** | **64 bits** |
| **Key Size (Logical)** | **64 bits** (8 parity bits → **56 effective bits**) |
| **Number of Rounds** | **16** |
| **Structure** | **Feistel Network** |
| **Round Key Size** | **48 bits** |
| **Subkey Generation** | **PC-1 → Circular Left Shifts → PC-2** |
| **Standardization Body** | **NIST (FIPS 46-3)** |
| **Year Adopted** | **1977** |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Syllabus Highlight:** In the Foundations of Cryptography Lab, the DES experiment tests a student's ability to *translate cryptographic theory into working Java code*, specifically handling **bitwise operations**, **permutations**, **S-box substitution**, and the **Feistel round function**. Implementing DES manually (without `javax.crypto.Cipher`) demonstrates core understanding.

---

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy: The "Locked Suitcase with 16 Locks"

> [!TIP]
> **Imagine a suitcase (your 64-bit data block) being secured by 16 different padlocks in sequence.**
>
> - The suitcase is split into two halves: a **Left Half (L)** and a **Right Half (R)**.
> - Each padlock (round) takes the right half, scrambles it, mixes it with a unique key (round subkey), and adds the result to the left half.
> - After all 16 padlocks are applied, the two halves are recombined, and the suitcase is sealed.
> - The 16 unique keys are all derived from a single master key, but each is slightly different (through circular shifts).
> - To unlock it, you walk **backwards** through the 16 padlocks — which works because the Feistel structure is **reversible** even though the round function itself need not be invertible.

This intuition captures the essence of DES: a **reversible cascade of irreversible-looking transformations**, secured by **16 derived subkeys** generated from a single secret master key.

---

## 1.3 Why DES Still Matters Academically

Even though DES is **cryptographically broken** for modern use (brute-forced in 1997's *EFF DES Challenge* in 56 hours, and in under 24 hours by 1999), it remains the **pedagogical foundation** of modern block ciphers (3DES, AES, Blowfish). For KTU lab examinations, implementing DES tests mastery of:

- **Bitwise operations** (`XOR`, `<<`, `>>`, `& 0xFF`)
- **Permutation tables** (lookup-based bit rearrangement)
- **Substitution boxes (S-boxes)** (nonlinear transformation)
- **Key expansion and scheduling**
- **Symmetric encryption/decryption symmetry** (same algorithm, reverse key order)
- **Hexadecimal I/O handling**

---

## 1.4 Java-Specific Implementation Strategy

A textbook DES implementation in Java typically uses:
- A `byte[]` or `long` to represent 64-bit blocks
- A `BitSet` (from `java.util.BitSet`) for arbitrary-length bit manipulation
- A `String` or `byte[]` for keys
- Static permutation tables declared as `int[]` arrays
- Methods for: `initialPermutation()`, `finalPermutation()`, `expand()`, `substitute()`, `permute()`, `xor()`, `generateSubkeys()`

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU Lab Note:** For practical Java code in exams, students often use a **64-bit `long`** (or two `int`s / eight `byte`s) instead of `BitSet` for simplicity, since `long` natively holds 64 bits in Java.
