# 📘 SECTION 4: Structural Diagrams & Schematics

## 4.1 Top-Level DES Encryption Flow (Mermaid Block Diagram)

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[64-bit Plaintext] --> B[Initial Permutation IP]
    B --> C[Split into L0 and R0 of 32 bits each]
    C --> D[Round 1 with Subkey K1]
    D --> E[Round 2 with Subkey K2]
    E --> F[Round 3 with Subkey K3]
    F --> G[Round ...]
    G --> H[Round 15 with Subkey K15]
    H --> I[Round 16 with Subkey K16]
    I --> J[Swap L16 and R16]
    J --> K[Inverse Initial Permutation IP_INV]
    K --> L[64-bit Ciphertext]
```

> [!NOTE]
> **Reading the diagram:** The cascade of 16 rounds forms the "Feistel ladder." The single arrow from $L_0 \to R_{16}$ and $R_0 \to L_{16}$ highlights the famous **half-swap property** at the end of Feistel ciphers.

---

## 4.2 Inside One Feistel Round (Expanded View)

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    Lprev[L sub i minus 1: 32 bits] --> X1[XOR]
    Rprev[R sub i minus 1: 32 bits] --> EX[Expansion E: 32 to 48]
    EX --> X1
    Ksub[K sub i: 48-bit subkey] --> X1
    X1 --> SBX[S-Box Substitution: 48 to 32 bits]
    SBX --> PX[Permutation P: 32 to 32]
    PX --> X2[XOR]
    X2 --> Rnew[R sub i: 32 bits]
    Rprev --> Lnew[L sub i: 32 bits]
```

> [!TIP]
> **Notice the data flow:** The right half $R_{i-1}$ is expanded, XORed with the subkey, substituted, permuted, and finally XORed with $L_{i-1}$ to form $R_i$. The new $L_i$ is simply the *old* $R_{i-1}$. This single round is then repeated 16 times.

---

## 4.3 DES Key Schedule Flowchart

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    K64[64-bit Master Key] --> PC1A[PC-1: Drop 8 parity bits]
    PC1A --> C0D0[Split into C0 and D0 of 28 bits each]
    C0D0 --> LSH1[Left Circular Shift by s1]
    LSH1 --> PC2A[PC-2: Select 48 bits]
    PC2A --> K1[Subkey K1]
    LSH1 --> LSH2[Left Circular Shift by s2]
    LSH2 --> PC2B[PC-2: Select 48 bits]
    PC2B --> K2[Subkey K2]
    LSH2 --> LSH3[Continue for 16 rounds]
    LSH3 --> PC2C[PC-2: Select 48 bits]
    PC2C --> K16[Subkey K16]
```

