## 4.4 Feistel Round Function — Internal Architecture

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    IN[Input R: 32 bits] --> E1[Expansion Table E]
    E1 --> ER[Expanded R: 48 bits]
    ER --> XOR1[XOR with Subkey K sub i]
    K1[Subkey K: 48 bits] --> XOR1
    XOR1 --> X48[48-bit Block]
    X48 --> S1[S1 Box: 6 to 4 bits]
    X48 --> S2[S2 Box: 6 to 4 bits]
    X48 --> S3[S3 Box: 6 to 4 bits]
    X48 --> S4[S4 Box: 6 to 4 bits]
    X48 --> S5[S5 Box: 6 to 4 bits]
    X48 --> S6[S6 Box: 6 to 4 bits]
    X48 --> S7[S7 Box: 6 to 4 bits]
    X48 --> S8[S8 Box: 6 to 4 bits]
    S1 --> CON[Concatenate 8 x 4 = 32 bits]
    S2 --> CON
    S3 --> CON
    S4 --> CON
    S5 --> CON
    S6 --> CON
    S7 --> CON
    S8 --> CON
    CON --> P1[Permutation P]
    P1 --> OUT[Output f of R and K: 32 bits]
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Why 8 S-boxes in parallel?** The 48-bit input is split into **eight 6-bit chunks**, each fed to one S-box. Each S-box is a **$4 \times 16$ lookup table** providing the crucial **nonlinearity** that makes DES resistant to linear and differential cryptanalysis. Without S-boxes, DES would be a trivially breakable linear cipher.

