## 5.4 📌 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!TIP]
> **Rapid Revision Checklist — DES Java Implementation**
>
> ✅ **DES uses a 64-bit block and 64-bit key (56 effective bits).**
>
> ✅ **Three stages: IP → 16 Feistel Rounds → IP⁻¹.**
>
> ✅ **Each Feistel round:** $L_i = R_{i-1}$, $R_i = L_{i-1} \oplus f(R_{i-1}, K_i)$.
>
> ✅ **Round function $f$:** Expansion (E, 32→48) → XOR with 48-bit subkey → 8 S-boxes (48→32) → Permutation P.
>
> ✅ **S-boxes are the only nonlinear step of DES** (provide confusion).
>
> ✅ **Key schedule:** PC-1 (64→56, drop parity) → 28-bit halves $C_i, D_i$ → circular left shift by $\{1,1,2,2,2,2,2,2,1,2,2,2,2,2,2,1\}$ → PC-2 (56→48).
>
> ✅ **Decryption = encryption with subkeys in reverse order** (Feistel property).
>
> ✅ **Standard test vector:** Plaintext `0123456789ABCDEF`, Key `133457799BBCDFF1` → Ciphertext `85E813540F0AB405`.
>
> ✅ **Java implementation tip:** Use `java.util.BitSet` for arbitrary bit manipulation, or a `long` for 64-bit blocks. Convert table positions using `inSize - table[i]` to bridge 1-indexed FIPS tables to 0-indexed code.
>
> ✅ **DES is broken for modern use** (1999 EFF cracker: <24 hours), but pedagogically essential.
>
> ✅ **3DES and AES** are its modern successors in real-world applications.
